MTF,<br><br>
You raise a good question. Lately I have taken to forcing myself to do some constructive things, like clean up the garage, or something! Anger and depression leaves a lot in its wake. Taking a long walk or relaxation routines help smooth over the rough spots.<br><br>
It's Ok to be angry, it really is! Our problemn is that we tend to confuse real anger with rage in all it forms, or get into the passive-agressive cycle.<br><br>
What is real anger? To me it is a self-esteem response to unacceptable behavior or circumstance. When &quot;I&quot; am &quot;here&quot;, I can get angry. When &quot;I&quot; am not &quot;here&quot;, things trigger rage.<br><br>
The two have entirely different feelings. Anger is a measured response to a real thing. Rage is an out of control response to an imagined or perceived thing.<br><br>
The things that cause anger are seldom the things that trigger rage. Cause and trigger, a real difference to me. <br><br>
We are all each other's Iktome. I am in a trauma processing group, and you never saw a more sorry group of Iktome in your life! We help each other to see, to cry, to feel, to love, to care.<br><br>
I am my own blind spot.<br><br>
I am proud and honored that we are Iktome to each other! There is no greater gift. <br><br>
Munch, munch, munch! Love thosa meetsa ballsa! &lt;G&gt;<br><br>
